{"file_path":"/project/IMPLEMENTATION_SUMMARY.md","content":"# Summary: Instant.parse() Consistency Fix

## Issue Resolution
Fixed inconsistent behavior of `Instant.parse()` between JVM/JS and iOS platforms when parsing ISO-8601 date-time strings.

## Root Cause
- JVM and JS implementations delegated parsing to platform-specific parsers (`java.time.OffsetDateTime.parse` and JS-Joda)
- Platform parsers were more lenient than documented, allowing optional seconds
- Native implementation correctly used the documented strict format
- This caused inconsistent parsing behavior across platforms

## Solution
Removed platform-specific delegation and made all platforms consistently use the custom `ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET` format.

## Files Modified

### 1. `/project/core/jvm/src/Instant.kt`
**Changes:**
- Removed special-case handling for `ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET` format
- Removed delegation to `java.time.OffsetDateTime.parse()`
- Removed `fixOffsetRepresentation()` helper function
- Removed unused import `java.time.format.DateTimeParseException`
- Simplified parse() to consistently use custom format

**Before:**
```kotlin
public actual fun parse(input: CharSequence, format: DateTimeFormat<DateTimeComponents>): Instant =
    if (format === DateTimeComponents.Formats.ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET) {
        try {
            Instant(jtOffsetDateTime.parse(fixOffsetRepresentation(input)).toInstant())
        } catch (e: DateTimeParseException) {
            throw DateTimeFormatException(e)
        }
    } else {
        try {
            format.parse(input).toInstantUsingOffset()
        } catch (e: IllegalArgumentException) {
            throw DateTimeFormatException("Failed to parse an instant from '$input'", e)
        }
    }
```

**After:**
```kotlin
public actual fun parse(input: CharSequence, format: DateTimeFormat<DateTimeComponents>): Instant =
    try {
        format.parse(input).toInstantUsingOffset()
    } catch (e: IllegalArgumentException) {
        throw DateTimeFormatException("Failed to parse an instant from '$input'", e)
    }
```

### 2. `/project/core/commonJs/src/Instant.kt`
**Changes:**
- Removed special-case handling for `ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET` format
- Removed delegation to `jtOffsetDateTime.parse()`
- Removed `fixOffsetRepresentation()` helper function
- Removed unused import `kotlinx.datetime.internal.JSJoda.OffsetDateTime as jtOffsetDateTime`
- Simplified parse() to consistently use custom format

**Before:**
```kotlin
public actual fun parse(input: CharSequence, format: DateTimeFormat<DateTimeComponents>): Instant =
    if (format === DateTimeComponents.Formats.ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET) {
        try {
            Instant(jsTry { jtOffsetDateTime.parse(fixOffsetRepresentation(input.toString())) }.toInstant())
        } catch (e: Throwable) {
            if (e.isJodaDateTimeParseException()) throw DateTimeFormatException(e)
            throw e
        }
    } else {
        try {
            format.parse(input).toInstantUsingOffset()
        } catch (e: IllegalArgumentException) {
            throw DateTimeFormatException("Failed to parse an instant from '$input'", e)
        }
    }
```

**After:**
```kotlin
public actual fun parse(input: CharSequence, format: DateTimeFormat<DateTimeComponents>): Instant =
    try {
        format.parse(input).toInstantUsingOffset()
    } catch (e: IllegalArgumentException) {
        throw DateTimeFormatException("Failed to parse an instant from '$input'", e)
    }
```

### 3. `/project/core/native/src/Instant.kt`
**No changes** - already had the correct implementation.

## Expected Behavior Changes

### ✅ Will Now Work Consistently (All Platforms)
```kotlin
// Parse with seconds - works on all platforms
Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50:30Z")
Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50:30.123Z")
Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50:30+03:00")

// Optional offset minutes - works on all platforms
Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50:30+03")
```

### ❌ Will Now Fail Consistently (All Platforms)
```kotlin
// Parse without seconds - fails on all platforms
try {
    Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50Z")
    // Throws DateTimeFormatException: "Parse error at char 16: expected char ':', got 'Z'"
} catch (e: DateTimeFormatException) {
    // Expected - seconds are required per documentation
}
```

## Documentation Alignment
The fix ensures behavior matches the documented format specification:

> From [ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET documentation](DateTimeComponents.kt line 72-73):
> "This format differs from [LocalTime.Formats.ISO] in its time part in that
> **specifying the seconds is not optional**."

Format structure (from DateTimeComponents.kt lines 103-124):
```kotlin
public val ISO_DATE_TIME_OFFSET: DateTimeFormat<DateTimeComponents> = Format {
    date(ISO_DATE)
    alternativeParsing({
        char('t')
    }) {
        char('T')
    }
    hour()
    char(':')
    minute()
    char(':')
    second()                    // NOT optional
    optional {
        char('.')
        secondFraction(1, 9)
    }
    alternativeParsing({
        offsetHours()
    }) {
        offset(UtcOffset.Formats.ISO)
    }
}
```

## Impact Assessment

### Positive Impact
1. ✅ **Consistency**: Same parsing behavior across all platforms
2. ✅ **Documentation Alignment**: Behavior now matches documented format
3. ✅ **Reliability**: Developers can test on one platform and expect the same elsewhere
4. ✅ **Code Clarity**: Simpler, cleaner code without platform-specific workarounds

### Breaking Change
- Code that relied on JVM/JS lenient parsing will now fail
- Only affects parsing **without seconds**, which was documented as invalid
- Most users should be unaffected as proper ISO-8601 format includes seconds

## Testing Recommendations

Verify the fix with these tests:

```kotlin
@Test
fun parseWithSecondsWorks() {
    val instant = Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50:30Z")
    assertNotNull(instant)
}

@Test
fun parseWithoutSecondsFails() {
    assertFailsWith<DateTimeFormatException> {
        Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50Z")
    }
}

@Test
fun parseWithOptionalOffsetMinutesWorks() {
    val instant1 = Instant.parse("2024-03-19T17:50:30+03")
    val instant2 = Instant.parse("2024-03-19T14:50:30Z")
    assertEquals(instant1, instant2)
}
```

## Status
✅ **Implementation Complete**
- ✅ JVM platform fixed
- ✅ JS platform fixed  
- ✅ Native platform unchanged (already correct)
- ✅ No compilation errors
- ✅ No lint errors
- ✅ Code simplified and cleaned up"}

